    <node id="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d0">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Respiratory-origin small particles and droplets that can carry infectious agents and remain suspended in air. Attributes: size distribution, airborne residence time, and potential to transmit respiratory infections; concentrations are influenced by source strength, ventilation, and filtration. Here Aerosols are the airborne exposure vector targeted by ventilation interventions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CARBON DIOXIDE">
      <data key="d0">CARBON DIOXIDE</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Indoor CO2 concentration (typically ppm) used as a quantitative parameter and practical proxy for ventilation effectiveness. CO2 reflects occupancy-generated exhaled breath and, under well-mixed and occupancy-driven conditions, correlates with outdoor air exchange rate (ACH). Caveats: CO2 is an indirect proxy and can be confounded by non-occupant sources, poor mixing, or local generation.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="35347782">
      <data key="d0">35347782</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">PubMed ID 35347782: a peer-reviewed article/record linked on the page that provides empirical data or analysis relevant to ventilation, aerosol behavior, and use of CO2 as a ventilation proxy. Serves as a referenced validation source for relationships among ventilation, aerosol concentrations, and CO2 monitoring.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.5</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HUMANS">
      <data key="d0">HUMANS</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">The human population and related clinical/public-health endpoints (e.g., inhalation exposure, infection risk) that constitute the ultimate effectiveness measure for ventilation and aerosol-control interventions in indoor settings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
