      <data key="d8">TRANSMISSIBILITY AND TRANSMISSION OF RESPIRATORY VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d9">VALIDATED_BY</data>
      <data key="d10">Leung (2021) provides mechanistic and epidemiologic context (modes of transmission, environmental modifiers) that supports the rationale for ventilation as a mitigation strategy against airborne respiratory viruses.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.82</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d14">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="VENTILATION" target="AEROSOLS">
      <data key="d7">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d8">AEROSOLS</data>
      <data key="d9">TARGETS</data>
      <data key="d10">Ventilation is designed to target airborne aerosols by diluting and removing aerosolized respiratory particles through increased outdoor air exchange, exhaust, filtration, or enhanced mixing. | Empirical and theoretical evidence indicates effective ventilation reduces airborne aerosol concentrations and thus inhalation exposure under appropriate ACH and mixing conditions.</data>
      <data key="d11">0.9</data>
      <data key="d12">1</data>
      <data key="d13">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_10</data>
      <data key="d14">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </edge>
